 these essays address the need for scholarship on women’s lives and experiences. Women in Early America heeds the call of feminist scholars to not merely reproduce male-centered narratives, “add women, and stir,” but to rethink master narratives themselves so that we may better understand how women and men created and developed our historical past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aWomenxHistoryx17th centuryxUnited States. 0aWomenxHistoryx18th centuryxUnited States. 0aWomenxSocial conditionsxUnited States. 0aWomenzUnited StatesxHistoryy17th century. 0aWomenzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aWomenzUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh1 aBerkin, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoster, Thomas A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMorgan, Jennifer L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479874545.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479876419423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479876419/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles